In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares April 9th, 2015, as National Former Prisoner of War Recognition Day. He honors the men and women who have been prisoners of war, acknowledging their sacrifices and the debt of gratitude owed to them. The proclamation highlights the unimaginable trials and cruelty faced by American servicemen and women as prisoners of war, including mental and physical torture, starvation, isolation, and indefinite captivity. Despite these hardships, these heroes displayed courage and determination, standing fast for their principles. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of never leaving members of the armed forces behind and the commitment to serving former prisoners of war, their families, and all veterans. President Obama calls upon all Americans, as well as government officials and organizations, to observe this day with appropriate ceremonies and activities to honor American prisoners of war, service members, and veterans.